## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to decompose a 128-bit value, apply a 64-bit bit-reversal, and reassemble in swapped halves to achieve full 128-bit reversal without branching.

## Key Concepts

- 64-bit bit-reversal via mask/shifts
- 128-bit composite type handling
- Endianness intuition for cross-half reversal

## Code Example

```c
typedef struct { uint64_t hi; uint64_t lo; } uint128;

static inline uint64_t reverse64(uint64_t x) {
  x = (x >> 1) & 0x5555555555555555ULL | (x & 0x5555555555555555ULL) << 1;
  x = (x >> 2) & 0x3333333333333333ULL | (x & 0x3333333333333333ULL) << 2;
  x = (x >> 4) & 0x0F0F0F0F0F0F0F0FULL | (x & 0x0F0F0F0F0F0F0F0FULL) << 4;
  x = (x >> 8) & 0x00FF00FF00FF00FFULL | (x & 0x00FF00FF00FF00FFULL) << 8;
  x = (x >> 16) & 0x0000FFFF0000FFFFULL | (x & 0x0000FFFF0000FFFFULL) << 16;
  x = (x >> 32) & 0x00000000FFFFFFFFULL | (x & 0x00000000FFFFFFFFULL) << 32;
  return x;
}

uint128 reverseBits128(uint128 x) {
  uint128 r;
  r.hi = reverse64(x.lo);
  r.lo = reverse64(x.hi);
  return r;
}
```

