questions.answer:
I'd implement this using a two-stage branchless compression: first compress each 64-bit limb independently from 64 to 32 bits using the standard bit-pack trick (mask and shift), then combine the results into the final 64-bit result. The key insight is that we need to: (1) mask every even bit, (2) shift to consolidate positions, (3) repeat for odd bits and merge.

**Signature:**
```c
typedef struct { uint64_t hi; uint64_t lo; } uint128;
uint64_t packEvenBits128(uint128 x);
```

**Justification:** Since we need 64 even-positioned bits from 128 bits, we compress each 64-bit limb to 32 bits, then pack as `(hi32 << 32) | lo32`. This uses only shifts, masks, and bitwise ops—no loops or conditionals.

**Quick tests:**
- `packEvenBits128({0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF, 0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF})` → `0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF`
- `packEvenBits128({0xAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA, 0xAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA})` → `0xAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA`

```c
uint64_t packEvenBits128(uint128 x) {
  uint64_t lo = x.lo;
  lo &= 0x5555555555555555ULL;              // keep even bits
  lo = (lo | (lo >> 1)) & 0x3333333333333333ULL;  // compress to 2-bit groups
  lo = (lo | (lo >> 2)) & 0x0F0F0F0F0F0F0F0FULL;  // compress to 4-bit groups
  lo = (lo | (lo >> 4)) & 0x00FF00FF00FF00FFULL;  // compress to 8-bit groups
  lo = (lo | (lo >> 8)) & 0x0000FFFF0000FFFFULL;  // compress to 16-bit groups
  lo = (lo | (lo >> 16)) & 0x00000000FFFFFFFFULL; // compress to 32 bits

  uint64_t hi = x.hi;
  hi &= 0x5555555555555555ULL;
  hi = (hi | (hi >> 1)) & 0x3333333333333333ULL;
  hi = (hi | (hi >> 2)) & 0x0F0F0F0F0F0F0F0FULL;
  hi = (hi | (hi >> 4)) & 0x00FF00FF00FF00FFULL;
  hi = (hi | (hi >> 8)) & 0x0000FFFF0000FFFFULL;
  hi = (hi | (hi >> 16)) & 0x00000000FFFFFFFFULL;

  return (hi << 32) | lo;
}
```

