## Why This Is Asked

This question tests advanced bit manipulation skills, specifically parallel bit extraction (PEXT-like operations) across 128-bit values. It evaluates the candidate's ability to design branch-free, constant-time operations that scale—skills essential for performance-critical code, cryptography, and systems programming.

## Key Concepts

- **Parallel Bit Extraction (PEXT):** Compact bits from a source value based on a mask, packing them contiguously from the LSB
- **Mask-Driven Bit-Slicing:** Process 128-bit data split into hi/lo 64-bit halves
- **Branch-Free Design:** Use only bitwise operations and shifts—no loops or conditionals
- **Logarithmic Compression:** O(log n) complexity via fixed mask/shift sequences

## Code Example

```cpp
typedef struct { uint64_t hi; uint64_t lo; } uint128;

uint128 compress128(uint128 x, uint128 mask) {
    uint64_t m = mask.lo;
    uint64_t d = x.lo;

    // Parallel extract bits from lo half
    d = (d & m) | ((x.hi & (m >> 64)) << 64);

    // Compression via perfect shuffle and merge
    uint64_t t0 = (d & 0x5555555555555555) | ((d & 0xAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA) >> 1);
    uint64_t t1 = ((d & 0x5555555555555555) << 1) | ((d & 0xAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA) >> 2);
    d = (t0 & 0x3333333333333333) | ((t1 & 0xCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCC) >> 2);

    // Final compression...
    return (uint128){d >> 32, d & 0xFFFFFFFF};
}
```

**Note:** The complete implementation uses a multi-stage logarithmic compression scheme that progressively narrows the bit spacing until only the selected bits remain contiguous.

