**Approach:** Fold the 128-bit value into a single bit using successive XOR reductions. By XORing the high and low 64-bit halves, then progressively folding via shifts, we accumulate all bit parities into the least significant bit.

```c
unsigned parity128(uint128 x) {
    uint64_t v = (uint64_t)(x >> 64) ^ (uint64_t)x;
    v ^= v >> 32;
    v ^= v >> 16;
    v ^= v >> 8;
    v ^= v >> 4;
    v ^= v >> 2;
    v ^= v >> 1;
    return (unsigned)(v & 1);
}
```

**Justification:** Each XOR-shift pair propagates parity information from larger to smaller bit regions. After the full sequence, bit 0 holds the XOR of all 128 bits—exactly the parity. This technique is O(log n) with no branches or loops.

**Tests:**
- `parity128(1)` → 1 (one bit set, odd parity)
- `parity128(0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF)` → 0 (all 128 bits set, even parity)

**Function Signature:**
```solidity
function reverseBytes128(uint128 x) returns (uint128)
```

**Justification:** We perform a cascaded byte-swap within each 64-bit half using masks and shifts. First, we swap adjacent bytes (1-byte stride), then 2-byte blocks, then 4-byte blocks—all confined within each half. Finally, we reassemble hi and lo back into a uint128.

**Implementation:**
```solidity
function reverseBytes128(uint128 x) returns (uint128) {
    uint64 hi = uint64(x >> 64);
    uint64 lo = uint64(x);

    // Step 1: swap adjacent bytes (0<->1, 2<->3, ...)
    hi = ((hi & 0xAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA) >> 1) | ((hi & 0x5555555555555555) << 1);
    lo = ((lo & 0xAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA) >> 1) | ((lo & 0x5555555555555555) << 1);

    // Step 2: swap adjacent 2-byte words (0-1<->2-3, ...)
    hi = ((hi & 0xCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCC) >> 2) | ((hi & 0x3333333333333333) << 2);
    lo = ((lo & 0xCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCC) >> 2) | ((lo & 0x3333333333333333) << 2);

    // Step 3: swap adjacent 4-byte words (0-3<->4-7)
    hi = ((hi & 0xF0F0F0F0F0F0F0F0) >> 4) | ((hi & 0x0F0F0F0F0F0F0F0F) << 4);
    lo = ((lo & 0xF0F0F0F0F0F0F0F0) >> 4) | ((lo & 0x0F0F0F0F0F0F0F0F) << 4);

    return (uint128(hi) << 64) | uint128(lo);
}
```

**Test Examples:**
- Input: `0x0102030405060708090A0B0C0D0E0F10` → Output: `0x0807060504030201100F0E0D0C0B0A09`
- Input: `0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF0000000000000000` → Output: `0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF0000000000000000`

