## Why This Is Asked
Rotations are fundamental in cryptography (e.g., SHA-2), hashing, and bitboard manipulation. Implementing them correctly on composite 128-bit types tests understanding of cross-word boundaries and careful handling of edge cases.

## Key Concepts
- Decompose 128-bit value into hi/lo 64-bit halves
- Handle k near 64 where rotation crosses half boundaries
- No loops required—just careful bitwise arithmetic
- Return early for k==0 to avoid undefined behavior with 64-bit shifts

## Code Example
```c
typedef struct { uint64_t hi; uint64_t lo; } uint128;

uint128 rotl128(uint128 x, unsigned k) {
    k &= 127;
    if (k == 0) return x;

    if (k < 64) {
        uint64_t hi = (x.hi << k) | (x.lo >> (64 - k));
        uint64_t lo = (x.lo << k) | (x.hi >> (64 - k));
        return (uint128){hi, lo};
    } else {
        unsigned k2 = k - 64;
        uint64_t hi = (x.lo << k2) | (x.hi >> (64 - k2));
        uint64_t lo = (x.hi << k2) | (x.lo >> (64 - k2));
        return (uint128){hi, lo};
    }
}
```

