```c
typedef struct {
    uint64_t lo;
    uint64_t hi;
} uint128;

uint128 transitions128(uint128 x) {
    uint64_t shifted_lo = (x.lo >> 1) | ((x.hi & 1ULL) << 63);
    uint64_t shifted_hi = (x.hi >> 1);
    uint128 y;
    y.lo = x.lo ^ shifted_lo;
    y.hi = (x.hi ^ shifted_hi) & 0x7FFFFFFFFFFFFFFFULL;
    return y;
}
```

**Justification:** Bit `i` differs from bit `i+1` exactly when `x_i XOR x_{i+1} = 1`. Shifting `x` right by one positions bit `i+1` at position `i`, so `x XOR (x >> 1)` yields 1 at every transition point. Bit 127 is masked to 0 because the shift discards the original MSB, leaving an undefined high bit that must be explicitly cleared.

**Tests:**
- `transitions128({0b11..., 0})` → `{0b00..., 0}` (no transitions: constant bits)
- `transitions128({0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF, 0})` → `{0, 0}` (no transitions within lo word)

Approach: swap adjacent bits within each 64-bit half independently. For each half, isolate the even-positioned bits using mask `0x5555555555555555` and the odd-positioned bits using mask `0xAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA`. Then shift even bits left by 1 and odd bits right by 1, combining them with OR.

**Signature:**
```c
typedef struct { uint64_t hi; uint64_t lo; } uint128;
uint128 swapAdjacentBits128(uint128 x);
```

**Implementation:**
```c
uinterp swapAdjacentBits128(uint128 x) {
  const uint64_t evenMask = 0x5555555555555555ULL;
  const uint64_t oddMask  = 0xAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAULL;
  uint128 r;
  r.lo = ((x.lo & evenMask) << 1) | ((x.lo & oddMask) >> 1);
  r.hi = ((x.hi & evenMask) << 1) | ((x.hi & oddMask) >> 1);
  return r;
}
```

**Justification:** Masking isolates even and odd bit positions, shifting rearranges them, and OR combines the results without collision. This runs in O(1) time with constant-space operations.

**Tests:**
- `swapAdjacentBits128({0, 0xFF})` returns `{0, 0xAA}` (0b11111111 → 0b10101010)
- `swapAdjacentBits128({1, 0})` returns `{2, 0}` (bit 64 moves to position 65)

