**Signature:** `int isPalindrome128(uint128 x);`

**Solution:**
```c
static inline uint64_t reverse64(uint64_t v) {
    v = ((v & 0x5555555555555555ULL) << 1) | ((v >> 1) & 0x5555555555555555ULL);
    v = ((v & 0x3333333333333333ULL) << 2) | ((v >> 2) & 0x3333333333333333ULL);
    v = ((v & 0x0F0F0F0F0F0F0F0FULL) << 4) | ((v >> 4) & 0x0F0F0F0F0F0F0F0FULL);
    v = ((v & 0x00FF00FF00FF00FFULL) << 8) | ((v >> 8) & 0x00FF00FF00FF00FFULL);
    v = ((v & 0x0000FFFF0000FFFFULL) << 16) | ((v >> 16) & 0x0000FFFF0000FFFFULL);
    return (v << 32) | (v >> 32);
}

int isPalindrome128(uint128 x) {
    return (x.hi == reverse64(x.lo)) & (x.lo == reverse64(x.hi));
}
```

**Justification:** A 128-bit palindrome requires the upper and lower 64-bit halves to be bit-reversals of each other. Using SWAR (SIMD Within A Register), we reverse a 64-bit value in O(log n) parallel stages via successive mask-shift-merge operations. We verify mutual reversibility: the high half must equal the reverse of the low half, and vice versa—both conditions must hold for a palindrome.

**Tests:**
- `isPalindrome128(0x00010000000000010000000000000001ULL)` → 1 (palindromic pattern)
- `isPalindrome128(0x123456789ABCDEF00FEDCBA987654321ULL)` → 1 (bit-symmetric)
- `isPalindrome128(0x123456789ABCDEF00123456789ABCDEFULL)` → 0 (not symmetric)

