questions.answer:
Approach: Compute the 128-bit popcount by counting each 64-bit half using the classic parallel bit-counting method, then summing the results. For both the high and low 64-bit halves, apply the following branch-free formula:

```c
uint64_t popcount64(uint64_t v) {
    v = v - ((v >> 1) & 0x5555555555555555);
    v = (v & 0x3333333333333333) + ((v >> 2) & 0x3333333333333333);
    v = (v + (v >> 4)) & 0x0f0f0f0f0f0f0f0f;
    return (v * 0x0101010101010101) >> 56;
}

unsigned popcount128(uint128 x) {
    return popcount64(x >> 64) + popcount64(x & 0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF);
}
```

**Justification:** This approach uses the classic parallel (SWAR) bit-counting algorithm, which computes popcount in O(1) time using only bitwise operations—no loops or conditionals. It works by successively refining bit counts across all positions in parallel, then collapsing via multiplication. The 128-bit version applies the 64-bit routine to each half and sums the results, maintaining branch-free execution throughout.

**Tests:**
1. `popcount128(0)` → 0 (all bits clear)
2. `popcount128(UINT128_MAX)` → 128 (all bits set)

