## Why This Is Asked
This question tests precise bit-manipulation skills across 128-bit data without loops or branches. It validates the ability to split work across halves and combine results safely while demonstrating understanding of efficient parallel counting algorithms.

## Key Concepts
- 128-bit values represented as two 64-bit halves
- SWAR (SIMD Within A Register) popcount on 64-bit words
- Combining two 64-bit counts to produce a 0-128 result
- Bitmask-based parallel computation

## Code Example
```c
uint64_t popcount64(uint64_t x) {
  x = x - ((x >> 1) & 0x5555555555555555ULL);
  x = (x & 0x3333333333333333ULL) + ((x >> 2) & 0x3333333333333333ULL);
  x = (x + (x >> 4)) & 0x0F0F0F0F0F0F0F0FULL;
  x = x + (x >> 8);
  x = x + (x >> 16);
  x = x + (x >> 32);
  return x & 0x3FULL;
}

uint64_t popcount128(uint64_t hi, uint64_t lo) {
  return popcount64(hi) + popcount64(lo);
}
```

